	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				In response to the actual post for a change, you don't need to spend a training point to do anything you don't need to gain a level for.  You can Fish, Tailor, fight with any weapon open to your class, cast any spell type (provided you aren't hybrid, which Druids are not, that's why melee is a last resort and something to start out your career), Blacksmith, Bind Wounds, Beg, you name it.  If your guild master doesn't tell you you need a higher level than first to learn a skill, you can do it immediately.  Now that first point takes the longest to earn so spending a point just to get the logs rolling is a good idea, but it's not required. It's better to save up for Channeling, Dodge, then Specialization.<BR>
<BR>
When I started, my sibling kept trying me to be a Necromancer or some other Dark Elf so we could hunt together once I caught up.  I really didn't want to be a Dark Elf and choose Halfling as a race.  Druid just looked like the most exotic of the available classes from there so I went with it.  I put all my points into the highlighted attributes, that's why they're highlighted, you are going to need them.  I tried pouring everything into Wisdom but I couldn't put the last five points there.  I am almost certain I put them in Agility, but if I had it to do again, I would've chose Charisma or maybe been a Wood Elf.  I got lucky making one of the &quot;best&quot; Druid archtypes, but I didn't have any coaching back then and only realized at level 19 that my favorite thing to do is Befriend Animals.  With my horribly, horribly low Halfling Charisma, the beast breaks the spell fast and sometimes before I issue my first Hotkeyed command.<BR>
<BR>
But I wanted to play a Halfling, not a Wood Elf and my low Charisma is tolerable.  Befriend Animal is improved every so often and sometime after level 50, the creature won't break the spell.  It's a long way off, but something to look forward to.<BR>
<BR>
If you are kicking yourself because you didn't start with the &quot;best&quot; Druid you could, then you almost certainly chose what you wanted to play.  There are so many magic items you can find that will set your most important statistics at 200 no matter how low it was when you began.<BR>
<BR>
One way or another, if you want boring, check out those Necromancers who gain levels like we gain silver coins who will for their whole lifes raise the dead, cast a poison spell, cast a sicken spell, convert health into mana, siphon the life from their targets, fear the baddies, and shoot them until they die only to learn more spells.  And if that isn't cool enough, these new spells do the same thing.  O they'll gain levels fast but have nothing to look forward to.<BR>
<BR>
Now take a Druid.  We are always welcome in any group because of our various talents starting at level five when you might first need to join a group, if not for our healing abilities, then for our ability to pacify entire Goblin or Orc camps with Harmony.<BR>
<BR>
At ninth, our improved Healing and blasting spells allow us to fill in any gaps in our current group.  We also get the first of a long line of Shield of Thistles spells, which helps keep monsters focussed on the Warriors because they cause the monster more pain the way.  At fourteen we get access to my favorite:  Befriend Animal.  This has it's own technique for those who like to fly solo.  It's pretty common but if you don't know it yet, find some nice animal friend.  The larger Bears work well.  Have him beat up some other poor sod and don't forget to coat him in Thistles.  Once the two of you kill a couple other monsters, the spell should lapse.  Either Root the Bear and try again if he's healthy or finish him off if he's wounded badly. You'll get credit for every creature killed, monsters and Bears.  Beyond that, there are the commonly known Bind Affinity and Wolf Speed, both which can make you enough money until you can teleport people around.  You also get upgrades to your defensive and offensive spells.  Among these is the first lasting damage spell you'll find:  Stinging Swarm.  All of these spells are great and charming animals is a great way to put a new twist in the run-of-the-mill hack n' slash or Snare n' blast strategies you've been using.  It's not &quot;better&quot; just breaks the monotony.<BR>
<BR>
If you tire of this by the time you hit nineteen, sorry, you don't get much of anything new yet but you do get many spells to increase the effectiveness of what you've been doing.  My favorite, of course, is Feral Spirit, which makes your animal companion stronger.  Again, you get betting Healing and blasting spells.  In fact, at nineteen, you can Heal as well as a Cleric of your level, only difference is they've been doing it for five levels already.  Of course, if you are getting tired of the same ol' same ol', while you won't find a much larger spell selection, you can now teleport to some basic locations and hopefully the change of scenery will tide you over.<BR>
<BR>
At twenty-four, you get the regular improved spells.  Creeping Crud replaces Stinging Swarm, Charm Animals is a stronger Befriend Animal, Ensnaring Roots is superior to Grasping Roots, and you can teleport to a few new locations.  Of particular interest is my other favorite, Wolf Form.  You move faster and attack better, sure.  But really its just a bunch of fun to run around as a Wolf.  Only an Enchanter gets to turn into more things than we do.  And even then, we're pretty restricted.<BR>
<BR>
At twenty-ninth we can now charge people to zap them off to other lands.  A common use for this is to get your buddies out of danger before they all get creamed, so it has three uses.  Of course, the first one you could do since nineteen if you don't mind leaving all your friends behind. Another Shield of Thistles upgrade, a Healing upgrade, the usual.  But no more is travelling to the best hunting ground going to take as much time as hunting there will so you'll find your group gains points a little faster than you might expect.<BR>
<BR>
At thirty-fourth, you get hugely powerful versions of area effect and damage over time spells, a greater range of teleportation destinations, Regeneration, and Strength of Stone.<BR>
<BR>
At thirty-ninth, you upgrade Shield of Thistles once again, Skin Like Diamond, and such but for that &quot;something new&quot; you are presented with awesome group spells. You can turn your whole company into Wolves, Regenerate your entire party, tote them off to even more exotic locations, and Pack Spirit.<BR>
<BR>
And it goes on like this.  Next you get an even stronger charm spell, and there's no reason you can't use it in a group.  It might be a good way to cut down on the number of targets hitting you.<BR>
<BR>
Either way, there will be something to keep your interest.  Maybe Druids aren't the best melee class, but those Griffins in Northern Karana are really tough and if you don't feel like ordering them to attack the local guards, have them fight each other and gether your friends around to watch the cock fight that they can't start.  okay, Enchanters can, but I'd like to see an Enchanter Teleport and run faster than a Druid.  Then again, I'd also like Clarity so I'll do anything for my Enchanter friends, and as far as I'm concerned, they are all my friends.<BR>
<BR>
I digress.  What I am trying to say is Druids are the coolest.  Not because of the race we choose, not because of our starting stats, or even what we get them to once we collect magic jewelry and such.  But because we have the widest range of spells of any class.  Any class.  If you want your Druid to spar Scimitar to claw with the nasties of the world, get make yourself a Ranger.  It's a nice alternative.  They get the really fun Druid spells, they can last through melee, and they can shoot the wings off a fly.<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
